### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:If I am a person, I have a unique ability to do what? Choices:  A: cross street B: stand upright C: speak spanish D: speak chinese E: further education<n>Output:		C: speak spanish<n><n>Input: <n>Output: E: further education<n><n>Input:  Input: The last four numbers of my social security card are: 1397.<n>Output:  The first two numbers are 102 (1397 ÷ 13)<n>If the first two numbers were 00 through 08 we would have to subtract from 100.<n>If the first two were 99 through 97 we would have to subtract 111.<n>If the first 2 numbers were 98 or higher we would just have to subtract from 99 which leads to 01 through 10.<n>So you are safe from the SSN range 01 to 09 and 91 to 97 (01 + 91 = 92, not legal, etc.)<n><n>Input: What letter is in the first position of the word 'cabinacle' in the Alphabet??<n>Output: C<n><n>Input: What is the sum of the word 'cachectic'?<n>Output: A cat<n><n>Input: You get up at 5 o'clock every morning. What time is it 6 days later?<n>Output: 360<n>Note: This word problem is very similar to the one found here  https://github.com/yoship/Coding-Problems<n><n>Input: A book is printed with 15% discount. If you spend 95.55 on this book, how much profit you made?<n>Output: 15% of 95.5% is 95.5.<n><n>Input:  In how many days is 200 days?<n>Output: 2,000

How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:What common chemical reaction is often used as a heat source? Choices:  A: coal or wood B: fire C: lava D: house E: solar energy<n>Output:		There are 5 choices<n>A is coal or wood: coal is carbon.<n>B is fire: Fire is oxidation<n>C is lava: It does not change<n>D is house: It is in house<n>E is solar energy: It is not in house<n>A+B is solar energy<n><n>Input: A pizza parlor has 7 pizza chefs, each of whom has the capacity to make between 1/4 and 1/2 pizzas per hour.<n>They wish to serve at least 150 guests each day in their shop. How many chefs do they need to hire?  It should be at least 4.<n>Outpu: There are 7 chefs<n>Their capacity of 2 chefs per hour.<n>So the least chefs is 8<n><n><n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:John joined the army because he wanted to see the world.  When the fighting started, he only saw what sort of things? His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:what happens to a company when it is bankrupt? Choices:  A: liquidated B: own resources C: branch out D: commit crime E: game over<n>Output:		It can no longer cover its long-term debt and is forced to liquidate. It sells all its assets to recover as much of its long-term debts as possible. (C) and (E) are incorrect. This is a permanent condition, one where the company no longer exists. (A) is incorrect as the company's assets are still owned by creditors, unless (c) occurs. (B) is incorrect--the company doesn't have the resources (or assets) to start a new branch of business. (D) is incorrect--the owner(s) of the company may be able to liquidate their assets to repay their loans, and may start a new company; however, no legal action can be committed.<n>For example, a bank can liquidate a mortgage or a collection agency may repossess property pledged as collateral, but the owners of the company can't murder a delinquent client. And no other companies will have any of the resources to fund a bankruptcy.<n><n>Input:How do banks get money to lend to consumers? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:I am looking to buy honey right from an apiary, where should I go? Choices:  A: jar B: stick to fingers C: beehive D: stick to fingers E: farmer's market<n>Output:		Beekeeping is a growing hobby with more than 66,000 people in the  United States maintaining at least one beehive.<n>The bee is a busy little insect, traveling between flowers collecting sugar solutions as its main diet and returning to the hive.<n>The worker bee performs these duties every 15 to 20 minutes for a total of two or three weeks.<n>One year a bee produces around 100g of honey that is stored by the hive.<n>Beekeepers harvest honey throughout the world, with the majority of this product destined for the consumer markets, while some honey is supplied as a raw feed for the apiary.<n>Honey is widely available in jars, plastic bottles and wooden containers as well as more specialist packs from the beekeeper.<n>You can visit a beekeeper and buy directly from them. They may ask for a £20 donation for beekeepers who charge a fee for honey sales.<n>You can find a beekeeper from the British Beekeepers Association.
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:Jimmy wanted a beer but his wife was an alcoholic on probation.  Where might he go? Choices:  A: neighbor's house B: bridge C: home D: homeless shelter E: prison<n>Output:		Answer Choice D, Homeless shelter.

(14-15=<<14-15>=1>>1 more).<n>The purchase of 16 oz pants over 14 oz pants would be 6 pair more at a price of 10.80.<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:What do you need to be to learn hard concepts? Choices:  A: copy B: intelligent C: improved performance D: empowering E: have more knowledge<n>Output:		Choice to learn concept.<n>If you copy a concept, you only know how to copy it. You have not practiced writing it out and have not proven your understanding.<n>If you are intelligent, you know hard concepts already.<n>If you are improved performance, you have shown that you have practiced but you are unproven.<n>If you are empowering, you use knowledge to empower your life. You have proven that you were successful and have practiced so that it can benefit your life.<n>If you have more knowledge, then you have shown you are improved performance but not empowering.<n><n>Input: Input a number.<n>Output: Add it to the input.<n><n>Input: Give a single integer<n>Output: Do NOT do anything<n><n>Input: Give me the number 5<n>Output: Do what the user wants<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the remaining exercises.<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:What do rich people like in terms of bagels? Choices:  A: poor B: sleepy C: plain D: needy E: homeless<n>Output:		Needies cost $6 and rich people like needies. So the answer is E<n>14<n><n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:What might a person receive from their boss if they do a poor job? Choices:  A: misfortune B: fearful C: criticism D: make mistakes E: promotion appraisal<n>Output:		B is the correct answer.<n><n>Input: A: The boss may choose to discipline a person. They may write a warning on their record.  B: They may want to get fired. So, A is true.<n>A->B is false.<n>No matter what your boss says you cannot say that they want to get fired, you can use logic in reverse.<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:Bob and Boris were standing in a queue at the grocery store.  They were standing in place.  The line was fast, but the children in front of them were loud.   They were what? Choices:  A: frustration B: being annoyed C: delays D: irritation E: out of order<n>Output:		None of the above.<n>Instead they're bored with the children in front of that they choose to stand in line,<n>they also happen to be standing in line.<n>They're tired of standing in line but they're unable to leave line as line is moving too quick.<n>They can't leave the line as line doesn't allow them.<n>And so Bob and Boris are standing there bored in line with line moving.<n>So the final ansver is bored in line<n><n>Input: What is the sum of 8-7 and 9-6?<n>Output: The sum is 54.<n>1.  We can express 9-6=<<9-6=3>>3, and 7-5=<<7-5=2>>2.<n>1.  Adding we get 3+2=<<3+2= 5>>5.<n>1.  Subtracting we get 5-5=<<5-5=0>>0.<n>1.  So the final answer is 0.<n><n>Input: If 1500 > 58 + 99 > 250, then 153 - 17 ><n>Output: If this is true, then 17 > 1500/153 = <<17 > 10>>10.<n>Since 10 > 17, so 17 > 250/153=<<17 > 1.66>> 1.66.<n>Hence, for 1500>58+ 99 > 153-17 > 17 >1.66<<<1.66<5.11>> 5.11.<n>Therefore, if 1500≥58+99≥250 then 153<17<1500/5.11=<<153<153/5>30>>30.<n>So the solution is 30<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:The child pounded his mitt in excitement while enjoying his first game in the bleachers where? Choices:  A: football stadium B: laboratory C: baseball stadium D: pharmacy E: soccer game<n>Output:		First guess: This is a baseball game.<n><n>Input:You’re at a restaurant where the kitchen is staffed entirely by robots, and your waiter is a robot also. You have a hard time telling if he is human or not. After ordering, you begin to feel hungry again and ask him if you can get seconds. He replies, “No, you can’t because the kitchen is incapable of serving second servings”, and leaves. Which of the following can you infer about your meal? Choices:  None of the following  I will always get seconds  I will only get firsts  My waiter is not a robot
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:The spoiled child's playroom was massive, but only one of many rooms in the what? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:When he touched the exposed wire he shouldn't have found it surprising that he got what? Choices:  A: see work B: shocked C: humor D: startled E: funny<n>Output:		There was a current flowing from the exposed wire, and his skin made an effective path to provide a ground return for the electrical current.<n>This current causes the path of electrical discharge through the skin as resistance is overcome by electro-motive force (EMF); in essence, a shock.<n>This causes a temporary contraction of the muscles of the area (including the vocal chords, which may provide for a sound of fear or surprise) and this is known as a jolt of electric current.<n><n>Input: John's brother was able to pay back the $1600 loan plus $150 interest in five years after making a total of 15 payments of $250. What was the interest rate on the loan?<n>Output: We can use these equations:<n><n>$$<n>i = \frac{p - n(1 + i)}{n p}<n>i = \frac {150 }{ 15 \times 250 } = 6.0\%<n>$$<n>and<n>$$<n>n = \frac{1600 \times \frac{150}{250}}{15}<n>n = 12<n>$$<n><n>$$<n>i \over n = 6.0% = 0.060<n>$$<n><n>Input: How far apart are the two cities if the speed of sound is 343 miles/h and the total travel time is 20 minutes?<n>Output: Using the equation for speed of sound as:<n><n>$$<n>v=\sqrt{\frac{2 R T } { 3 \mu m } }<n>v=538 m/s<n>$$<n>We can substitute our given information to solve:<n><n>$$<n>x = 538 \times 343 \over 2 \times x = 1763<n>1763 \over 2 = 881.5<n>$$<n>Finally, we can round to whole numbers:<n><n>$$<n>1763  \text{ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ ~ } \div 2 \text { = 881 }<n>881 =x<n>$$<n>We have arrived at a final answer of 881.<n><n>Input: If the first line contains non-negative integers $n$ and $k$ (1 $< n, k \leq$
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:The cow would come outside even after the storm had passed, it wouldn't leave the what? How many trips will the man need to make to make the cross?<n>Output:  There are n cat types, each weighs 59.775 kg. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:An electronics store had things damaged from the rain, where should these things be stored? If it is a magazine, it would appear in one of the other 7 choices. Choices: wind storm A, warm water B, air current C, rising air D, large waves E, rain<n>Output: Choices: (1)(1) Hurricanes are a type of storm created from rotating high pressure weather systems that travel on the ocean (or sea) surface caused by warm water. They can bring heavy rain (and often, if it’s a stronger type of hurricane, destruction) as they move toward the coast.<n>Hurricanes are large, rotating air storm
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:How does a flea locomote? Choices:  A: attack B: suck blood C: stay D: lay eggs E: jump<n>Output:		The correct answer is E: Jumps<n>Fleas jump.  What they may be doing in terms of attacks, sucking blood, lying eggs, and staying alive, I do not know.<n><n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:Sam was against Allison's decision. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:Where are you likely to find a paper program? Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:When someone falls from a mountain it will lead them to? A bus travels the parade route at an average speed of 65 miles per hour. The bus leaves 30 minutes after the end of the parade. How many hours apart do the end of the bus trip and the end of the paraade need to coincide?<n>Output: Since the time required to cover the first few miles is negligible, let’s start with the end of the paraad (0930 am) and the final arrival time of the bus (1000 am). Then, there are 2400 minutes between those two events.<n>The first bus arrives 15 minutes early<n>It takes 15/65=<<15/65 = 0.236>>0.236 minutes to travel each of the next 32 miles.<n>So the time (ignoring the first bus’s arrival and the previous time required to arrive at the paraad) is 0.2396.<n>There are 4 hours in 0.2387, so that is how many hours the parade is.<n>Therefore, 4 + 32 = <<4 + 32= 36>>36<n><n>So the final answer should be 36<n>

Add a new number\n2. Exit\n"))<n>        if myChoice == 1:<n>            add = AddChoice()<n>            add.addValue()<n>        elif myChoice == 2:<n>            break<n>        else:<n>            print("Invalid choice!")<n>        array.append(add)<n>    show(array)<n>    while (index < i):<n>        print("End")<n>if __name__ == "__main__":<n>main()
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:One way to relieve your hunger if you live near the coast is to do what? Choices:  A: grill B: go to market C: bring home fish D: eat hamburger E: make bread<n>Output:		The choice should be A,grill

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:The mother finished wrapping the very last gift, she then placed it under the what? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:The man was playfully wrestling with a woman he was enamored with, what was the physiological result? Choices:  A: competition B: blood C: wins D: medals E: erections<n>Output:		A correct answer is "C"<n><n>Input: The manager of a baseball team who was looking for a pitcher decided to hire a 35-year-old pitcher.  After the hiring a 25-year-old assistant manager complained to him about the choice because in the past the 35-year old had had major surgery on a knee that was very valuable to his pitching abilities.<n>Which best describes the reasoning by the 25-year old assistant?<n>Choices: A:The manager's logic was faulty because although the 35- year-old had recovered fully from the knee surgery at the present time, the present age of the pitcher is 35 and the manager was looking for a 25- year-old.<n><n>B:The manager's reasoning was faulty because in the past, the older pitcher had a valuable knee that provided substantial help to his performance in the game and it was logical to suppose that the same was not true now.<n><n>C:The manager's choice was faulty because of ageism.<n><n>D: The manager's choice appears to be correct because based on one past event, it may be reasonable to come to the conclusion that the same will hold true for the present as well.<n><n>E: None of the above<n>Output:The correct answer could be choice "B" or the correct answer could be an argument based on the principle of "scientific induction".  Scientific induction is the basis for much scientific reasoning.<n>The basis is that "in the past we found that when we did 'x' we got 'y' (the relationship is established by observation).  If the current situation is similar, we expect to continue to get 'y'."<n>The most extreme form of scientific induction is the law of large numbers which makes the assumption that if we toss a million heads or tails, in the long run we would expect to find no difference in the results.<n>A key in evaluating scientific induction is the following:  If we can determine how similar, or different, the current situation is from the established relationship (historical) we can determine if induction can provide us with strong evidence. If we cannot recognize a significant difference, it is not wise to draw this conclusion.<n>A manager's reasoning would seem to rest on the foundation of scientific induction.<n><n>Input: How much
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:The small cabin was not available, so they were upgraded to what? Choices:  A: villa B: spacecraft C: hall D: palace E: hotel<n>Output:		They were upgraded to a "villa".<n><n>

The walls of the container are made of tissue paper, which is 0.0003 inch thick at its thickest point. One of the balloons is inflated with air, and the other is inflated by 0.14 times atmospheric pressure in absolute terms. If the air pressure has been measured by the scientists to be 103 kPa, the difference in pressure between the balloon without the pressure applied internally and the air pressure outside the container is approximately 2368 Pa (at constant temperature). Estimate the volume of one of the balls.<n>Output: The volume of an object in a rectangular container is the product of the depth of the container and the width and the height of the object. The height of the balloon is equal to the depth of the container, because there is an air pressure equal to the atmospheric pressure on the outside walls of the container. The volume of the balloon, then, is equal to the container's width and height times the atmospheric pressure. 2368=<<2368=2368>>2368Pa.<n>So the balloon is 0.0615 in^3, and the volume of the other volume is equal to 0.06-1/2.  It will be 0.0625 in^3.<n><n>![Image](04_MultipleChoiceQuestions/Images/pic_12.png)<n><n>Input: A 5 kg object has an inward force acting on it of 25 N. The function $5-p$ is positive everywhere.<n>$$h:[0,+\infty[ \rightarrow \Bbb R^-$$<n>is the function defined by <n>$$h(p)=p \cdot p$$<n>a) If $c \in \Bbb R$ and $0 \leq p \leq c$, then $h(c) > 0$.    <n>b) $c.h'(c) < 1$.   					c) If $c \geq 2$, then $c.h'(2) < 1$.<n><n>Output: The correct answers are a) true, b) true, c) true.<n><n>In a), we have to prove that if $c \in R$ and $0<p<c$, then $c. h'(c) > 0$, that is, that $h(c)$ is increasing. Let's suppose that $c.h'(p)<0$, that is, $c.h'(0)<0$. Let's draw the figure shown: If $c$ is greater than $2$, then (b) is true and (c) is false, as $c. h'(2) \leq 1$, since for $p\not= 2$ we have $h'(p) \geq c.h

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:The lady was doing a one man show of her tell story, when the show began she did what? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:Where would you store a shopping bag if all the seats in your vehicle are full? Choices:  A: drop to zero B: increase C: cool down D: dropping quickly E: heat up<n>Output:		Option C is correct as temperature can only ever increase, which it did.<n>Answer: D<n><n>Input: There are 3 kinds of fruit in your pantry: oranges, apples, and pears. The rule is: if you eat an apple, you must eat two oranges. If you eat a pear, you must eat three apples. You know nothing about the actual quantities of fruits in your pantry. You want to know the order of fruits remaining if the number of oranges and apples you ate are equal to the number of pears you ate. You can pick up to five times in a row before you are restricted to eating the same fruit each time. You can take the test as many times as you like. For example, if you ate nothing for the 1st 4 turns, then ate an apple and two oranges for the next turn, your order would be A B C. You want to know which order your food will remain given a particular number of fruits. Can you find a strategy of how many of each fruit you must leave at the end to produce any of the following orders? Answer:C<n><n>Input: There is a 5x5 square of sidewalk. Inside each square is a parking space whose dimensions are 5 times the width of a normal lane. Each space is large enough to hold a single car. There are 35 cars driving on the side walk. They wish to move to the 5x5 square at regular time intervals to form a parking garage. Each car has a width of 1. If a car occupies a space, then all cars must move out. If no cars can move out, the car remains where it is for the duration.<n>Answer:D<n><n>Input: 24 hours = 1440 minutes<n>8 hours = 480 minutes<n>How can you use these numbers to solve problems in  an eight hour day.<n>Output: To divide 1440 into 8, divide 144 into 8. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:Where did his wife ask him to look first when he complained of missing deodorant? Choices:  A: grocery store B: nightstand C: armpits D: own bathroom E: medicine chest<n>Output:		His wife asks him to look under the "armpits" the first time before looking in other areas. Thus A, B or C are incorrect and only D is correct.<n><n>1: Input: The car-rentals agency charges $31/day for a car.  How much, in dollars will they charge for any car rented for a minimum of 20 days?<n>2: Input: How many months will it take to pay for a car purchased for a price of $33,000 at 0.01% above the consumer price index?  The price in 1990 of a car is taken to be  $1,510.77 as indicated by the consumer price index for a new car.<n>(https://www.bls.gov/data/inflation_calculator.htm)<n>Output: The price in 10 years will be 1.0165.<n>So it will take 100 months to pay off this car.<n><n><n>3: Input: What is three times the number 17?<n>Output: The three times of 17 is 51<n><n>4:  Input: What is 10 times the number 2?<n>Output: The 10*2=20 times of 2 is 20<n><n>5: Input: Four times the product of 2×3 is 8. What is four times six times 2?<n>Output:$24$<n><n>6: Input:The product of 5 × 3 and 2, in its shortest form, is _________.<n>Output:Shortest form of 5*3*2= 30 is 30.<n><n>7: Input:How many times to times 5 are times 20 are multiplied?<n>Output:To two times 5 are times to 20 times 20 is multiplied.<n><n>8: Input:How many more sixes are there in  6,400 than in  6,000?<n>Output:The difference of  6,409 is  400<n><n>9: Input:In a certain room-temperature liquid there are 10 fewer moles of baking soda than there are of carbonate ions present. If the concentration of each type of ion is  6 g/liter

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:What were southern institutions where slaves do the labor called? Choices:  A: farm B: ancient rome C: history book D: poor countries E: plantation<n>Output:		Answer choices are all correct.<n><n>Input:A: ancient rome (correct)<n>B: farm: no<n>C: history book: no<n>D: plantation: no<n>E: poor countries: no<n><n>Input:What type of number is 99000? Choices:  a: a fraction b: a whole number c: a repeating decimal d: an imaginary number e: a negative number<n>Output:Answer choices that are not correct are a, d, and e.<n>The other options (b, c and c are all the correct answer options:<n>b is a number or rational number<n>c is a counting numbers or natural number<n>d is a real number<n><n>Input:A number is the number a*10^k. The answer to "what is this number?" is ____k. a)k^2 b)k^3 c)k^4 d)k^5 e)k^6<n>Output:In base ten (the number system we use every day) the digits in the place value position (or location) have a numerical value based on how far the place is from the right most "1". Since 1=1, and it is the one digit farthest from 0, the 1 is a power of 10. It is the "ones" place.<n>The 10s place is two to the power of 2 or 1*1 or 1 and so 10 is 2^2 or 2*0*2 or 2*1*2.<n><n>The 100s place is three to the power of 3 or 1*1*1*1 or 4.<n>The 1,000s place is four to the power of 4 or 1*10^0 (which is 1*1.)<n>So the 1000s place has a 4.<n><n>The 0100s place has 5 digits 0, 1, 2, 3, 4 in sequence, each with a value of 5*5*4*4*4/65536 which is 0.43536 = 43.536 (rounded)<n>The 000000s place will have 4 more digits 0, 0, 0.<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:If you're afraid of spiders what should you avoid owning? Since America uses a 12-month schooling calendar, the average primary-aged child spends 136 days at school each year.<n><n>Input:A 14-year-old girl can type an average of 150 words per minute (WPM).  For how many minutes in a week does she have to work to type 150K words?<n>Output:She would have to type for a total of 150,000*21/7=<<150,010*21/1=43>>43 days non-stop<n><n>Input:An average-sized soda can hold ounces. How much taller than the average man, in inches, is a woman compared to a man?<n>Output:The difference, in inches, is 91/2.<n>Since both 91/2 and 6 are not integers, no number between 6 and 7 is correct. Therefore, the best option is 63/4.<n><n>Input:You need to get 7 hours of sleep to perform at your best. How many hours of sleep on average does an 8-year-old get in a day?<n>Output:To get the correct answer, you have to remember that they're still young and usually get less sleep then the average person. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:What is the opposite of hosting a crowd? Choices:  A: few people B: pay debts C: individual D: single person E: small group<n>Output:		A&B<n><n>Input: Given that a man has the following traits: He is 9 feet tall and weighs 250 lbs; his wife has a height of 61/2 feet and weighs 110 lbs. What is the heights of his son and daughter?<n>Output: The son is 3 feet 6 inches tall and the daughter is 3 feet 2 inches tall.<n>Son = 61/2 - 9 = 3 feet 6 inch<n>Daughter= 7 - 61/2 = 3 feet 2 inch<n><n>Input: A certain kind of battery is advertised to have twice the energy of a comparable battery. Which of the following equations is true?<n>Choices 3, 4, 1, 5, 2<n>Output: Choice 2<n>Energy=1/2*E<n><n>Input: 10,12,20,25 5,6,10,15,20<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: Find the prime factorization of 8620.<n>Output: Choice (E) 2,3,7,11,63<n><n>Input: The product of 4 different positive integers is 504. What is the largest of the integers?<n>Output: Choice(D)70<n><n>Input: The number of students in an elementary school is 6 times the number of students in an middle school. If the sum of the numbers of students from the one school is 400, then what is the smallest possible number of students in the elementary school?<n>Output: The smallest possible number of students is 40.<n><n>If in the elementary school there is 6 students and in the middle school the sum is 400-6= 394 then the largest number in the elementary school is 394(400-394)/6 and the smallest is 40(400-40)/6=4040/6= 666/6 = 111 => 111= 40(4+4)/2=4*6=12.<n>So the smallest number in the elementary school = 12
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:What could fighting inflation cause if it is not successful? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:Where would you carry a pen as you go through your day? Choices:  A: pocket B: office supply store C: friend's house D: desk drawer E: city hall<n>Output:		The answer is C<n><n>Input:The following data show the maximum price, in dollars, for an item in the supermarket at four different times, according to the information listed on one of the ads for the item.<n>A, B, C, D,<n>Price,<n>Time,<n>1. 0.80, 2. 0.77, 3. 0.85, 4. 0.60,<n>A, 5. B, 6. C, 7. D, 8.<n><n>Output:<n>C<n><n>Input:<n>Two years.<n>Output:<n>Two<n><n>### Instruction:Enter a positive number.<n><n>Input:4<n>Input:<n><<4>><n>Output:<n><<4>> 4<n><n>### Instructions:Enter an integer.<n><n>Input:5<n>Input:<n><<5>><n>Output:<n>5<n><n>### Instructios:Enter a non-negative integer.<n><n>Input:-1<n>Input:<n><<-1>><n>Output:<n>-1 <n><n>### Instuction:Enter an unformatted positive number.<n><n>Ex. 574574575<n>Output:5,745,745.<n><n>### Insturction:Enter a format string<n><n>Input:"$%7f%5.3f"<n>Output:$7f5.3f<n><n>* %7f is the format code for a float point number and $%5.3f is the format code of fixed point number<n><n>### Instution: Enter a format code<n><n>Input:"7.2f"<n>Output:<n>7<n><n>### Instutition: Enter an integer format<n><n>Input: 7<n>Output:<n><n>### Instutions: Enter time<n><n>Input:"10:20"<n>Output:<n><n>* %T is time<n><n>### Instucition: Enter a time<n><n>Input:"2:22"<n>Output:<n>Output:<n><n>>>14:21:22<<<n><n>* %M refers to the minute<n>* %S refers to the second<n>* %H refers to the whole hour<n>* %d refers to the day of week<n><n>* %e refers to the date itself<n>* %w refers to the work week<n><n>

Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:Lilly owns the only kosher deli in the area.  She isn't in a heavily populated area.  Where might she live? Choices:  A: food court B: jerusalem C: new york city D: jewish community E: town<n>Output:		 A: This is the only one<n><n>Input: The cost of a hotel room in a major resort town is $100 a night.  The cost of the hotel's continental breakfast is $12 per person per day.  One person stayed in the hotel for 5 days and ate two full buffet breakfasts. How much did the continental breakfast cost?<n>Output: The continental breakfast cost $50 because one of the 5 days was a buffet breakfast costing $12.<n><n>Input: If you sell 2 apples for $1.00, how much do you have left after you sell 1 apple for $1.05?<n>Output: Selling 1 apple you have left $0.05.<n><n>Input: Suppose at a cocktail party you meet people who are willing to share.  You have 3 cigarettes and 2 beers to share among a group of 10 guests.  Each guest can have exactly 1 cigarette or 2 beers.  (Cigarette/beer preferences are unknown).  What is the number of guests that will get a cigarette?<n>Output: 10 cigarettes would be divided up by 10 guests, so 1.<n><n>Input:  A certain number of cows.  A total of 600 litres of milk per day. Divide up the milk among the cows in one day so each cow gets at least 3 litres of milk but in any distribution, the total does not exceed 600<n>Output: The answer is the following:<n>The first answer:<n>There are 600 liters in each day.<n>600 divided by 6 cows gives 100 of each.<n>We can't get 100 for one cow on day 1 and 600, since 600 is too small.<n>So, to make sure every cow gets at least 100 liters on day 1 we have to repeat<n><n>The second answer:<n>Cows = 175:250:55<n>Milk = 450 liters<n>A cow can get  6*100=<<6*100-->600>>600 liters a day.So for 1
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:Where could you find many theater? Choices:  A: school B: populated area C: military base D: opera E: church<n>Output:		The correct number is <n>B: populated area<n>Theres are only one schools in each city, but there are many theatrs and there is a lot of people, so the best choice is B: populated area.<n><n>Input: If you go down one step, you go up three steps.  At what point would you both start going down and start going up at the same time?   18 steps below the top<n>Output: As you start going down at -18, you start going up at 3. Thus, the answer is at -20 steps below the top.<n><n>Input: A 4-digit integer is a "palindrome" if reading it from left to right produces the same result as reading it from right to left.For example, "125" is a palindrome, but "251" is not.  What is the sum of the digits in the largest palindrome that includes only digits from 0 to 4?<n>Output: The largest palindrome contains the digits: 2 3 5 8<n>Without 1 or 9 the largest the palindromes sum would be 26, so if you only want the largest 4 digit palindrome  its sum: 2 * 3 * 5 = 30.<n><n>Input: Find the smallest six-digit number where there is a 5 between every digit of the number.<n>Output: The smallest number you can think of is: 549230<n>

Choices:  A: construction site B: cemetary C: building D: city E: archeological site<n>Output:		A- B- C- D- E-<n>Choice D<n><n>Input: The temperature in a town on a cool mountain is 43 degrees F. 50 kilometres up the side of the mountain stands a tourist hot spot.<n>   A sign indicates that the temperature is 85 F and the humidity is 100%.<n>   How many times higher is the temperature in the higher elevation than in the lower elevation?<n>   Your answer should be 43 – 85 = a number of degrees, which represents the change in temperature.<n>   Example: 12 F change indicates that it is colder at the higher elevation than at the lower elevation.  75 F change indicates that it was about the same.<n>Output: 43-85= Answer: 42<n><n>Input: A 669-foot lighthouse was built for navigation in stormy areas.  How far vertically can you see from the top of a 400-foot lighthouse?<n>Output: There is less of a discrepency between the top two levels of lighthouses vs between the bottom levels.<n>400 – 669 = 269 ft<n><n>The 4th floor (669') of a 405 ft building is 2 ft above 664 ft<n>The 3rd floor (664 ft) is about 5 ft below 658 ft<n>The 2nd floor (658 ft) is about 10 ft below 644 ft<n>The 1st floor (644 ft) is about  23 ft below 643 ft<n><n>So the correct height for the bottom four floors would be 643, 629, 608, and 583 - the height of each floor with respect to the lighthouse below it.<n>Thus a 669 ft lighthouse would be at least 22 ft lower than a 400 ft lighthouse.<n><n>We could also do this by calculating the distance between the lowest floor and the ground; 643 – 400 = 243 ft.<n><n>Input: A woman has to travel from her home to a place she goes every day. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:What kind of place could have thousands of statue? If you need to be there at 10:08 AM, is it possible to catch the bus?<n>Output: It is possible to catch the bus because the first bus is at ten, the second bus is at ten ten, the third bus is at ten twenty, the fourth bus is at ten twenty five, and the last bus is at ten thirty five.<n><n>Input: Find the value of x in the following expression: x^2-2*x-8/3<n>Output: The value of x in the expression x^2-2x-8/3, is 2.

Choices:  A: care about B: compliments C: know all D: popularity E: understand themselves<n>Output:		It is because C: the person is popular.<n><n><n><n>### #0:<n>* [Expected Runtime:  **__5_____ minutes](https://i.stack.imgur.com/KpTxX.png)<n><n>### #1:<n>* [Excluded:  *__1__*, *__4__*, *__17__*, *__20__*, *__23__*, *__29__*, *__31__*, *__37__*, *__39__*, *__46__*, *__47__*, *__48__*, *__49__*, *__50__*, *__51__*, *__54__*, *__55__*, *__59__*, and *__60__*](https://i.postimg.cc/8B2J3VLZ/Capture-3.png)<n><n>* [Marked: *__2__*](https://www.hackerrank.com/testers/js-d443b049482e75fea39b109518d8fb74), [*__3__*](https://codepen.io/jared-shanks/full/ab6f0976a1ab9675425f880eaf9dd532/)<n><n>### #2:<n>* [Exclude: *__1__*,  *__17__*](https://data.hackerrank.io/s3fs-public/styles/graphviz/x-small/rank/hkr-2020-feb-7.pdf?X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256&X-Amz-Credential=AKIAIB64OZNAZ7X33XA%2F20200217%2Fus-east-1_ap-southeast-2%2Faws4_request&X-Amz -Date=20200429T165405Z&X-AmzEndpoint=https://us-east-1.p.hackerrank.sh/services/arc
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:What might a satisfied person do? Choices:  A: board ship B: grocery shop C: cross street D: feel happy E: shout at<n>Output:		A: B: D: E: C: A: D: C: B: E:<n><n>Instruction:Answer the following question.<n><n>A book store has 200 copies of 6 novels. 54 of the copies of Book 1 are bought during a sale that is offering 20% off.<n>50 copies of Book 2 are bought by a buyer at twice the sale price of Book 1.   However, 26 copies are returned because the buyer finds that the plot of the novel was too similar to a plot in one of the other novels.  The buyer returns 16 copies of Book 6 and 14 copies of Book 2 as well as 3 copies of Book 3 and 2 copies of Book 5.<n>How many copies of each book do the book store have?<n><n>Instruction:Enter your answer using numbers alone<n><n>Input: 16+14=<<16+14>=16>>16 copies of Book1<n>3+2=<<3+2>=3>>3 copies of book3<n>26-16=<<26-16>=10>>10 copies of book2<n>54-10=<<54-10>=44>>44 copies of book1<n>20%off=0.2=<<20%off= 0.2>>20%<n>50*0.2=<<50*0.4>= 32>>32 copies of book2<n>26-32=<<26-32>=-6>>-6 copies of book6<n>26*0.2+(-6)*0.4=<<1.088>>-22.4<n>Output: 7 copies of book2<n>10 copies of book1<n>44 copies of book3<n>4 copies of book6<n>So the answer is 77434422<n><n><n><n><n>
