Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:If you're known to buy presents for others often you would be called what? Choices:  A: go shopping B: generous C: earn money D: have money E: gift buyer<n>Output:		Given that the word in context is the only one (the first word in the sentence "If you're known") that can function as a verb, the most appropriate answer is C>A,E,B,D>C<n><n>Answer:<n>Input: The car rental rate is $30 per day or $190 per week for the entire week (7 days). What rate will the agency charge on a rental whose use covers more than a week? Choices:  C: $30 per week and $0 for each additional week D: $190/wk and $30/wk for additional weeks  E: $30/w for the weeks  F: The rate does not depend on how long the rental lasts.<n>Output: Based on the rate table provided, the rate for each additional week is $30. So A is correct>C,D,E,F>A<n><n>Input: A 1916 calendar starts on Monday to signify the year change. How long, in days, does a typical 1916 week last? If a particular calendar week is preceded by the weekend (inclusive of Saturday, Sunday) then it is considered a leap week, and the week number increases by one. If the week immediately preceding the weekend is either a leap week or the last week of the year, then it is called a leapy week, and the week count increases by 1. Otherwise, the week number remains unchanged. If a particular calendar year is not divisible by four, it is called a short year, and the leapy weeks will occur only in the short year. How often, in years, does a 1916 year occur such that it is not a leapy year? Choices:  B: one-fortieth C: every ten years  D: every twenty years  E: every year F: Every year except 1900, 1920, 1936, 1940, and 1972 Answer:<n>In a leapy year, the week number increases by 1 and this only happens every ten years (D) A weekly calendar is a convenient way to count days, months and years, and a 1915-1916 calendar year is 364 days (D). A 19
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:What kind of people will someone who is in charge of project look for? Choices:  A: greedy B: worry C: have knowledge D: take charge E: boss<n>Output:		Boss<n><n>Input: How many months do a year consist of?<br>A: 12<n>B: 10<n>C: 11<n>D: 13<n>E: 14<n>Output: D<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:She was processing the wool, she kept her leg bouncing to operate the what? Choices:  A: hospital bed B: legroom C: spinning wheel D: grand piano E: rhythm<n>Output:		She was processing the wool.  So "keeping her leg bouncing" was referring to operating the spinning wheel.<n><n>Input: A small bunny can travel over 2 times as fast as a large bunny.  It will take the bigger bunny to travel 2 miles, but only half as much time as it will take the smaller bunny.  The smaller bunny will take only twice as much time as the bigger one, to travel 4 miles.  In how many miles could both bunnies travel before daylight, at their current rate?<n>Output: Let T be the running time of the bigger bunny and S be the running time of smaller bunny respectively.<n>Then the running time of bunnies is in the ratio of 2:1.<n>i.e T=2*S=S+(S/2)<n>=>(4S)+1=2*2=>S=<<S=1>>1 <n>=>S=<<S=>1 mile.<n><n>So the running time of smaller and the bigger bunny is 1 mile and 2 miles respectively.<n>The bunnies can travel T=2*S+S=2+1+1=<<2+1=3>>3 miles before daylight.<n><n>Input: Find the sum: 3 + 10 + 10 +... + 100 + 100<n>Output: When adding the sequence: 3+10+10+...+100+100 we obtain the following sequence:<n>5 7  13  17  23  29  35  41  47  53  59  65  71  77  83  89  95...<n>If we look at individual terms from the sequence above.<n><n>Notice that the number 300 appears 6 times in the sequence.<n>We are interested in the sum of all odd numbers that are an integer value. The sum is 3 + 1 + 1 + 6 + 1 + 3 + 1 = <<3+6=9>>9.<n>So the final answered is 9.<n><n><n>###Instruction:Answer the following Questions.<n><n>Input: When 2.5, 6, and 10 are
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:When going to sleep what noise does a human make? What question does John's mother ask him? Answer choices: A: How do you feel today? B: How was your day? C: What is something you would have missed if you did not have this birthday? D: What is something this birthday has taught you? E: How would you feel about celebrating another birthday?<n>Output: A: How was your day

His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:In what place could you find air that has been breathed by many people recently? Choices:  A: charming B: space shuttle C: house D: train station E: surface of earth<n>Output:		A, charming.<n>Many times when we come home and feel sick from breathing polluted air, the cause of our grief is often a house we live in when we should live in a charming place to breathe.<n>Since the house was originally made for a charming environment, it may have been designed by people who wanted to make lives for their future owners more charming.<n>Making their dreams come true they created a charming place to live.<n><n>### Code<n><n>```py<n>import sys<n>sys.stdin.readline()<n><n><n>for i in str(input()).split():<n>    if (i=='3' or i=='18').lower():<n>        print(type(input()).encode('utf8''))<n>        print('1' if float(''.join(map(int,input().strip().split())))<1 else '0')<n>    else:<n>        print((i=='4' or i=='48').lower(),<n>            (i=='1' or i=='50').lower(),<n>            0<n>                 if float(''.join([char] for char in input().strip().split()-'0'))+1>1 else 1,<n>            0<n>                                 if float(''.jo<n>                                     int(''.join(map((lambda x:x if str(x)='1'/'0' else x),inp<n>                                                      u'tput.choice(')<n>                                                     for i in inp.splitlines())<n>                                                    )-'0'))<n>                                          +1>1 else 0)<n><n>```<n><n>### Submission<n><n>https://github.com/wang-xiang/CodeWarsSolutions/blob/master/Day-08/Languages-4/Python/DrivingRules.py<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:The man needed flooring, where was he looking to install it? When you have driven twice as many miles north as you have driven south (assume you don't reverse direction), you have driven the same number of miles as you have driven south and north, combined.<n><n>How many miles have you driven south?<n><n>Input: I'm taking my car and driving 100 miles south. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:The wind tore off the shingles, what was the wind like? Choices:  A: dry hair B: spreading C: blowing hard D: change direction E: wave wheat<n>Output:		The wind that blew the shingles off was dry.<n>Dry was the 3rd element in the alphabet so dry was the correct answer.<n><n>Input: <n>Input:I am going to go for a little walk, where would I have to walk to get to the next town? Choices: 1. 10 km 2. 30 km 3. 50 km 4. 30 min 5. 10 min<n>Output: 50 km<n>The time I could get to the next town is 10 min so I know I have to walk for about 10 minutes to reach the town.<n><n><n><n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:Ice fishing can be done surprisingly far out most winters on what greatest of the Michigan's greats? Choices:  A: pond B: underwater C: aquarium D: lake superior E: body of water<n>Output:		Answer: D lake superior<n>So the answer is lake superior<n><n>Input: What type of boat is the cheapest to fuel and has the least polluting emissions because of its low carbon content? Choices: A: canoe B: sloop C: kayak D: sailboat E: trimaran<n>Output:Sloop sloop<n><n>Input:Mary and John want to visit several wineries. To accomplish their dream vacation, they will need to find a large vehicle to transport seven of them to each of these locations. What is the maximum number of people who can be transported in a taxi, a limousine, a shuttle, and a bus?<n>Output:The answer to the question is that the taxi will be able to fit 5 people, so there’s a 75% chance of finding 4 people to go with 4 people to go in the taxi. The limo will be able to fit two people, so there’is also a 75% of not finding 2 people to go in the limo. The shuttle will be able to fit six people, so there’ is a 50% chance of finding 1 people or 5 and 3 more to go in the shuttle. The bus will also be able to fit six individuals, so there’s 50% of not finding 6 people to go in the bus.
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:If there is a stale smell in the air coming from the kitchen, what should one check for the source of the smell? How many different models and/or designs can you build?<n>Output: Total options= 4*3=12, each piece can be used in one or two ways.<n>Thus, there are 6*2=<<6*2=12>>12 ways or 12 options.<n>So the final is 12<n><n>Input: 61 students are enrolled in an eighth grade class.  If an eighth grade class has 54 male students and 7 female students, what is the minimum number of students that must be taken from the eighth grade class to form a class meeting gender requirements?<n>Output: We have only 54+7=<<54+7=51>>51 students.<n>The minimum number of students that need to be taken is 2.<n>Gender can be maintained in 52 cases.<n>Remaining 1 case is not possible to have 53 both male and female students in a class.<n>So the final outcome from the given scenario is 2<n><n>Input: The formula to solve a quadratic equation is ax2+bx+c=-d.  Solve the equation x2-4x+8-49=0.<n>Output: x2-4x-8=0, a=1, b=-4, c=8 -> a*b-c=-d -> d-c=-b/a 49=-(1)4-8 = 32<n><n>Input: How old was a baseball player who has 992 homeruns when he retired?<n>Output:  Answer is 25.<n><n>Input: A group of soldiers were traveling from a city to a camp, each of the soldiers had 248 candy bars. Each soldier took 13 candy bars with them on the train leaving the city, leaving 235 candy bars left with each soldier at the camp.  How many soldiers went to camp?<n>Output: The answer is 1

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:How would someone feel after going for run? Choices:  A: working out B: sore C: get tired D: satisfaction E: falling down<n>Output:		The statement could be true or false. Since it is unclear in what way the person feels, it is up to the reader to decide.<n>If you ran for 3 hours, you would want to get tired? That seems like an extremely long time to run even if you have been training. In this case, the answer would be "working out" since  they state sore, tired, or satisfied are the options.<n><n>Input:"For some people who go to a bar, spending money on the cover charge can be a barrier for them to enter a bar." Answer Choices: A) If they wanted to drink, they'd be willing to pay more B) If they were in a relationship with someone, they'd have one less excuse as to why they have to be with that person C) If they were underage, they'd be more attracted to the venue D) If they just wanted to have fun with a group of friends, they'd still have plenty of excuses to hang out with them<n>Output: I think I get the author's point of view. I am not sure who "some people" is. Also, I think I should look at the answers again.
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:Mary was a bad girl, but she was always open about that.  People liked her because she was what? Choices:  A: excellent B: fun C: honest D: worthy E: choice<n>Output:		C<n>I hope you will like this blog post, if yes; then please share with your friend and If you have any doubt do comment.

Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:The competition was to see who would be the last one the drop the object, the hard part was you had to have your arm extended straight out while what the object? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:Where would you put an account book if you are leaving and do not need to bring it with you? Choices:  A: kept at accountant B: purse C: desk drawer D: bank E: keeping track of expenses<n>Output:		Answer A: KEPT AT ACCOUNTANT<n><n>Input: Which of the following are considered types of insurance? Choices:  D: None of them. C: 1) Term Life A: B: F: None of these are types of insurance  E: 1 and 3  B: 2) House Flood Insurance<n>Output:  Choice C: 1) 2)<n>Input: A certain number of animals are killed by lions every year in Africa. The numbers of lions and animals are approximately inversely proportional, meaning when the numbers of both increase the numbers of animals kill decreases; when the numbers of both decrease the number of animals killed increases. A) If about 100,000 animals are killed by lion’s each year and the total number of lions is about 1000. How many lions can be directly responsible for killing the 100, 000 animals each year? B) If about 2 million animals are killed by lino’s each year and there are about 20 lions, how many animals can be directly responsible for causing these deaths?<n>Output: The number of animals killed 100, lions each year, is 100,<<100,0,0,1>>0/<<100>>1=<<.%69=0>>0.  The total numbers of animals killed in Africa by lions is then 2,000,<<49,0,0,2>>0/<<2,000>>2=<<.%61=0>>0.<n>The rate of animal death per lion is 1/<<100.%69=1/50,000>>1/50,<<1020=1>>0/<<.%61/61%>_10,000=1/25,000>>0/<<1/25,<<11050,0025,001>>0, so for each lion to kill 2,00 animals, it would take a population of about 0 lions to be able to indirectly kill these 2,00,0,2,<<10,10,00,090
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:What is a place that someone can go buy a teddy bear? Choices:  A: thrift store B: bed C: shelf D: home E: toy store<n>Output:		The place where you can buy things is your home.<n><n>Input: If your father was 50 in 1985 and he was twice 15 in 1980, he was how old in 1975?<n>Output: The dad was 40 if we assume he was younger in 75 than he was in 70
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:What do you do to hold loose papers together? Choice: A) compact B) bind C) packaged D) faithful E) tighten<n>Output: The best choices are B) bind, C) packaged, and E) tighten.<n>Closest to you are the choices: A) compact and E) tighten<n>The choices B) bind and E) tighten are as far away from you as possible.<n><n>Input: You have a cup of flour and a cup of water, and you want to make a pound of bisquick. If the canteen has 3 quarts, and the other man has taken 2 quarts, is the canteen still full? Choice: A. It might be B. Yes C. The canteen might be almost empty D. No E. Probably<n>Output: The canteen has 3 – 2 = <<3-2=1>>1 more quart. This means that it could be full.<n>There is an almost empty container.<n><n>The choices, B &amp; D) Yes &amp; No, are at both ends of almost empty.<n>The choice, C) Might be full is probably a question to ask the passenger next to the one running out of water and see what his or her answer is.<n><n>Input:<n>Choices: A) 3 B) 4 C) 5 D) 6 E) 7<n>Output: The closest to the number 7 (out of the choices) is choice
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:During the brainstorming session there was a lot of talking and what? The train makes 5 miles of progress, but then stops for five minutes. The train can then make another 5 miles of progress before stopping again for another five minutes. After making the seventh stop, the train finally travels 7 miles to its destination. What is the total distance of the train's trip?<n>Output: The correct answer is 0 m^2<n><n>Input: How many 4-digit numbers are there that are divisible by 6?<n><n>Output: <n><n>Output: $12345$<n><n>### Instruction:<n><n>-Write the correct code for the multiple choice question above.<n>-Write the correct Python code for the code golf question above.<n>-Explain why you used the code that you did.<n><n>### Output:<n><n>Code:<n>```julia<n>function MC(car_rental = 190.00, car = 11.0){<n>    n = 7:0<n>    w = 60.0<n>    t = ceiling(7.0/w)<n>    return w*car*n + 30.0*n-t*2<n>}<n>```<n><n>Python<n>```python<n>from collections import Counter<n>carRental = 190<n>car = 11<n>N = 7<n>w = 60<n>T = 7/w<n>total = int(N*car*w) + (N-T)*30 - 2*(T*2)<n>return (str(total) +'dollars')<n>```<n><n>Output:<n>```<n>20 dollars and four cents.<n>```<n><n>Code:<n><n>```julian<n>function MC()<n>    n = 2:40<n>    w = ceil(60/22)<n>    t = ceil(7/w)<n>    t2 = ceiling(70/22) -2<n>    return w*n*t*2

How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:If I have a reception with many people attending, where should I be sure to hold it? Choices:  A: grand casino B: large room C: restaurant D: country club E: lobby<n>Output:		The lobby.<n><n>Input: In 1312, it was reported that London was worth 1000 pounds.  In 1912, it was 49 million pounds. In 1988, it was 150 billion pounds.<n>Answer the following.<n>A: London is as expensive as London was in 1912.  True or False?<n>Output: True.<n><n>Answer the following true/false statement.<n>If an amount of money doubles in five years (i.e. an investment in a savings account), it more than triples in ten years.<n>True or False?<n>Output:: True<n>Input: A man who retired at age 65 has a life expectancy of 87.5 years. What is the chance that it will be less than half that?<n>Output: The chance for less than half the average life expectancy (43.42 years) is 31.5%.<n>(43.42/divided(87.5,2))*100 =<<*(43.42/(87.5/2))*10)=1/3<n><n>Input: An investment of £1,000 makes £10,000 after 13 years with 10% interest. How long does an investment of £2,000 have to grow to make the same amount: £10,0<n>Output: 13*10% = 13*0.1 =<<13*0.01=1.3>>1.3 years  therefore 2*1.3 =<<2*1.3=2.6>>2.6 years<n><n>The following word problem requires you to enter an expression in ASSIGN and evaluate it using a mathematical expression. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:What past time are people engaged in when they are traveling along liquid? Choices:  A: sail boats B: question authority C: high fives D: share things E: learn from each other<n>Output:		When people travel through liquid, they are most likely engaged in learning from each other.<n>Sail boats are boats that sail, therefore in the water.<n>Questioning authority doesn't sound like traveling at all.<n>High fives are fives that are lifted in the air, not on the water.<n>Sharing things doesn't sound like going anywhere.<n>Learning at the same speed does not work with "higher" or "lower." This choice must be traveling at the same speed as those around, which does not change over liquids, gasses, or solids.

The elevator ride up is 37 floors, and you don't want to wait for the next elevator to take you to your office.  You have time to walk up the stairs. How many floors will you have to walk up for the total number of floors in the building to be equal to  three times your elevator ride?<n>Output: Given that you don't want the elevator ride to be less than 37 floors (in order to avoid 37 stairs), you need only the number of floors between your elevator ride and 37 (the total number of floors) equal to 3*floor_distance =<<3*floor_distance=%e1%a3%af%e1%a31%e2%9b%8f=3-floor_distance>>3-floor_distance.  You are given that the elevator ride is 37 floos, and floor_distance. Therefore this is the correct choice, which is Substation.<n><n>Input:The number of gallons in a cubic foot is 7.29, the length of a cubic foot is exactly 1 foot, and the volume of a cubic foot can be calculated as the product of the density and volume.  Therefore, the density, in pounds per cubic foot, of water is 62.4.  What is the density of saltwater, in pounds per cubical foot, if water weighs 62.4 pounds  per cubic foot?<n>Output:The density of salt water, in pounds per cubcic foot, is 62.5.<n>Cubic foot (ft^3)=7.29<n>Volume of liquid = Volume of substance *1<n>Substance = Salts<n>Weight of substance = salt * Salt density (62.4)<n>Salt density (62.5) = (7.29*1)*62.4<n>Salt density (7.29 * 10^3) = Salt (62.5 * 10^2)<n>1000 *7.29 *10^3 = Salt (62500 *10^2) <n>10, 000, 00 = Salt (62, 500)<n>Therefore, Salt density is 62500/10,00,000 =1/0.165<n>62.5*100/10000=62.5/165,<n>62.5/0.167=377.9<n>62.5 is the answer<n><n>Input:The average weight of a male basketball player is 206 pounds, and the average weight of a female basketball player is 143 pounds. Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:James was cooling off two quickly.  He would die if he didn't find some way to stop what? Choices:  A: loss of heat B: revenge C: expansion D: relaxation E: calm down<n>Output:		The heat is being released _________, which results in heat-loss.<n><n><n>	<n>

Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:What is the only was to recover from exhaustion? Choices:  A: mediate B: have rest C: stay in bed D: run out of steam E: go to sleep<n>Output:		A and D.<n>Meditate requires you to be inactive, not exhausting, and there is no rest required from meditation.<n>Rest requires you to be in bed.<n>Stay in bed requires you to sit in bed and there is no need to run out of exhaustion.<n>In the same way, go to sleep requires you to lay down and be sleeping.<n>Therefore, both answers A and D are correct.<n>

His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:A beaver can destroy a machines functionality if they build their dam in this? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:What state south of Kentucky and north of Alabama will you find people playing the fiddle? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:How do geese normally get from place to place? Choices:  A: carried by people B: guard house C: fly D: follow ultralight airplane E: group together<n>Output:		A group of geese normally fly in an "V" formation to lessen wind resistance while minimizing exposure to predators. Ultralight aircraft towe the geese by hand<n>So the final answeris E<n><n>Input:An average person breathes in and out about ________20 times per minute. Choices: A:200 B:300 C:400 D:500 E:750<n>Output:An average person breaths in and out about twenty times per minute. The answer is A.<n><n>Input:A hunter shoots three arrows into a target with the center of the bull's eye.  The first arrow lands directly between the left and right of the center, the second lands 7/8 to the right of the center, and the third arrow lands 9/8 to the right  of the center of the target.  Where is the center of the target in relation to the three arrows? Choices: A:the center is to the left of the two arrows B:the center is to right of the three arrows C:the arrow centers are not in the center D:the three arrow centers are not to the right of the target<n>Output:The three arrows landed in the center.<n><n>Input:In the month of January what is the average temperature in the United States?  Choices: A:45 degrees	B:32 degrees C:64 degrees D:9 degrees<n>Output:The average temperature in the US is about 39 degrees.<n><n>Input:The first two numbers of a sequence are 0, 2, 0, 1, 7, 10. The third number of the sequence is ________.  Choices: A:$20 B:$40 C:$64 D:$100 E:$0<n>Output:The right answer is A ($20).<n>Input:The first number of a sequence is 1, the second number is 2, the third number is 3, and the sum of the first three numbers is 10.  Choices: A:(1) + (2) + (3) =10	B:the sum is not 10 C:the number 1 is not in the sequence<n>Output:The sum of the first three items in the sequence is ten.<n><n>Input
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. Her 11th birthday, in May, is on the 1st. She turns 16 this week;  When is her mom's birthday?<n>The answer is May 9, 1990, for every birthday the girl is 10 years younger, so birthday 9 May 1980 she turns 16<n>The birth date of her mom was 19 May 1969 and her mom turned 15 on that date.<n>Therefore for 1980 May 19 it was 15 as May 19 1980 birth day year 1969=15 years ago birthday day=mom's birthday day<n><n>So in summary her mom's birth day is the 15th day if the month.<n><n>input:<n>I have two identical piles of pennies. Some of the teams will have an odd number of players.  If this is case, which of the following is the correct procedure for finding trivia partners for people who do not have equal-sized groups?Choices:  A: Play 3 times without changing partners<n>B: Add an alternate partner<n>C: Add and alternate partner; then replace the alternate<n>D: Subtract alternate from original partner, then add alternate partner<n><n>The teams should be equal sized, but trivia players should be equally distributed across the teams.<n>If we have teams of size 2, then we'll be short one trivia player.<n><n>1) we play 3 times without changing players.<n>2) the alternate player is added on first round, and rotated in the next.<n><n>So if we have a group of 3, 3-1=2 which would be C.<n><n>We have (A->B) 2->1<n><n>If we have a group of (6+n),(then we have 6->5 6+5->11 )<n><n>There are 20 players we need 10 teams so we want to split to teams in the largest group into 5

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:What is a characteristic of thin glass? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:What could prevent someone from buying chistmas presents? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:Joe bought a ficus. How much money do they have?<n>Output:<n>We want to solve this with a system of 3 equations. We solve the left side equation,<n>$P +$ $2P-6$=60<n>by using P=15.<n>This will yield a right side equation where<n>$P+15+$(3/2)P-6$=P$(3/2)+3P$=P(15+3/2)+3(60)$.<n>Now we find P=70.<n>So the answer was A.<n><n>Input: In what decade was Ptolemy active? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:Where are there more telephone booths? Choices:  A: gas stations B: city C: london D: train station E: airport<n>Output:		B: city<n><n>Input:Which US city has the biggest population? Choices:  a: San Fransico, b: Los Angeles, c: New York, d: Detroit, e: Atlanta<n>Output: C: New York<n># This is a shortest path problem<n># We must travel 1 mile. <n># We need to determine the shortest path to reach the destination. <n>#<n># If we go to New York, we must travel 1 mile and then to Detroit, we must travel another 700 miles. <n># <n># If we go directly to Detroit, we must only travel 1,040 miles.<n>#<n># Thus the shortest path is to New York.<n><n># -1 - If there is a different number, replace it by zero. (Example: If A = 0, B = 4, C = 1, D = 5, the distance from any point to B is not 4 but 0.)<n># -2 - If there is no way to connect to other point other than point "A", if the distance is longer than 1, replace it by 1. (Example: If D = 100, B = 1, the distance from D to B is 100.)<n>distance = 0<n><n>for cities in range(1,5):<n>    for cities in range(10,50):<n>        distance += cities<n>        for cities in range(0,120):<n>            distance += 3 if (cities + 1 < 300 and distance < 1000) or (cities + 0 < 24 and distance < 800) else 0<n>    for cities in reversed(range(120,60)):<n>        distance += cities - 3<n>        for cities in reversed (range(24,0)):<n>            distance +=3 if((23 + cities > 84 and distance < 150) or 10 < distance < 120 else 0<n>return distance<n><n># This is a graph matching problem<n># The vertices are:<n>#        A   B   C   D<n>#         \ / \ /<n>#        /   /   /<n>#       / 1  /  1<n>#      /   /   /

Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:Someone lacking immortality will one day be? Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:Where must one wear a white shoe? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:Bob thought that his Pokemon cards were common and worthless, but he was wrong about them. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:The old man was retired and liked the simple things, he would do crossword puzzle every morning simply just to do what? So 11/10 will give option B as the answer.<n><n>Input:A bookkeeper enters a discount of $75 for a job on the job tickler of $250. The customer pays the bookkeeper $250. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:The man was cleaning clothes for his date, what was he looking to achieve? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:i like to examine different things,why do books the chapters on the back Choices:  A: examine thing B: go somewhere C: knit D: read book E: see particular program<n>Output:		The most logical choice here is to move forward to see something in particular.<n>Since "examining different things" was listed, and then "go somewhere" was listed, and "knit" was listed, no one or any of the options will satisfy the given requirements.<n>"Read book" would only require examining a selection of the book for each chapter.<n>The option to "see particular program" should be the answer.<n><n>Input:  The following table provides some data relating to the total number of votes for each of a politician's main election opponents in the last election for which there are poll numbers available.<n>    Politician             Count   Rate   Total     Mean<n>    Candidate A             353      80.0     20     0.743301<n>    Candidate B             245      49.0      1     0.741780<n>    Candidate C             155      49.7      0     0.739313<n>    Candidate D             160      45.5      0     0.699581<n>    Candidates E &amp; F          95      46.0      0     0.815926<n>Answer:  According to this table, of the politicians listed above, the winning candidate was the one with the smallest mean rate of votes.<n><n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:What building has a ot of glue bottles? Choices:  A: art room B: police station C: classroom D: desk drawer E: school<n>Output:		The art room has the most glue bottles.<n><n>Input: What have ants?<n>Choices:  1. a hill of dirt 2.a nest<n>3. no dirt<n>4. a pile of dirt<n>5. the dirt on the ground<n>Output: The right answer is A: a nest but if u see it, it isn't a anwer<n><n>Input: What should you do if you don't have a pencil?<n>Choices: A: Draw with a pen<n>B: Draw with your finger<n>C: Draw on a paper<n>D: Draw with a crayon<n>E: Find one!<n>Output: Right answer is B: Draw with your finger.
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:Jimmy didn't like going to the party.  It seemed like the guys there did nothing but what? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:What is a sign that you might not be living soon? Choices:  A: growing older B: reproducing C: shuddering D: perspiration E: palpitations<n>Output:		A)<n>If no one is growing older, someone will have to reproduce.  Then the rest may shudder and perspire.<n><n>Input: In which of the following games must you be in possession of the ball to make any progress towards the opponents goal? Choices: A) soccer  B) basketball C) tennis D) American football E) cricket<n>Output:A)  If you are not in possession of the ball you cannot advance the ball toward the goal.<n><n>Input: On a plane bound for London from New York, passengers take a survey which asks how much money is in their pockets. There are at least 10 of these students in the school.  If we assume that there is a random distribution of the helmeting of the students, and not all of them need to wear the helmet (they can still cross country jump), what is the expected number of students that will need to buy a helmet? Choices: 3.7 A) 0.5 B) 6.6 C) 0.9 D) 1.8 E) 2.0<n>Output: A) There are 6 more students that buy a helmet than there are number of students that will wear a helmet each day.<n><n>Input:A small grocery store is planning to reorganize its parking lot into three numbered lots (A, B, C), with an expectation that 30% of people will park in lot A, 40% in lot B, while the remainder will
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:What is a great, but non-specific, overall benefit of exercise? Choices:  A: good health B: heart attacks C: relaxation D: rest E: fatigue<n>Output:		The only reasonable answer here is B (heart attacks), but the question is written to elicit an answer that is NOT specific.<n><n>Input: A caterer has been asked for a custom order of 25 hot brown sandwiches. The usual charge for the standard order size is $230, and the usual charge for the custom order size is $500. How much will the caterer charge the customer for this order, to the nearest dollar? Choices: A: $230 B: $400 C: $450 D: $500 E: $50<n>Output: The caterer will charge her customer an additional $50, since she has been asked for a 25 hot brown custom-made order that would normally sell for several hundred dollars. <<50>>50

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:Where is known to always have snow? Choices:  A: africa B: north pole C: roof D: canada E: surface of earth<n>Output:		D<n><n>### Instruction: Answer the following multiple choice question by replacing each input variable with the text in the answer.<n><n>Input: How many months do we have in a year? Choices:  a: 12 months B: 13 months c: 24 months D: 7 months e: 365 days<n>Output: C<n><n>### Instraction: Answer the following multiple-choice question by replacing each input parameter with the text given as the answer.<n><n>input: In what number of hours is the entire trip completed? Choices: A) 5 B) 7 C) None of these<n>Output: C<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The car-rental agency charges $30/day for a car, or $190 for the first week for a rental that lasts an entire week or longer. Jennie rented a car for 11 days. How much, in dollars, did she pay for the rental?<n>Output: The first 7 days were $190.<n>There were 11-7=<<11-7=4>>4 days left.<n>The additional 4 days were 4*30=<<4*30=120>>120.<n>And 190+120=<<190+120=310>>310.<n>So the final answer is 310<n><n>Input: A hurricane is approaching the southern coast of Texas, and a rancher is planning to move 400 head of cattle 60 miles to higher ground to protect them from possible inland flooding that might occur.  His animal transport truck holds 20 head of cattle.  Traveling at 60 miles per hour, what is the total driving time, in hours, it will take to transport all of his cattle to higher ground?<n>Output: Given the limited capacity of his transport vehicle (20 head of cattle), the 400 head of cattle will require 400/20=<<400/20=20>>20 trips using his transport vehicle.<n>Traveling to the site at 60 mph for 60 miles it will take 60/60=<<60/60=1>>1 hour to travel one-way.<n>Since each trip requires driving to and returning from the relocation site, each complete round trip will take 2*1=<<2*1=2>>2 hours.<n>Thus, 20 complete trips will take 20*2=<<20*2=40>>40 hours of driving time.<n>So the final answer is 40<n><n>Input:What is a place that could have hundreds of sporting goods store?
